    "slug": "turkey-e-visa-expansion-excludes-somalia-despite-close-ties",
    "summary": "Turkey has added nine African nations to its e-Visa program, but Somalia, a key strategic ally, was left out. Somali travelers must still apply via embassies.",
    "content": "Turkey recently broadened its electronic visa system to include citizens of nine African countries, yet Somalia—a nation with which Ankara has cultivated strong diplomatic and economic partnerships—was notably omitted from the list. The expansion, announced this week, allows passport holders from Algeria, Cabo Verde, Egypt, Equatorial Guinea, Libya, Mauritius, Namibia, Senegal, and South Africa to obtain visas online. However, Somali citizens remain ineligible and must continue the traditional process of applying through Turkish diplomatic missions or authorized centers.\n\nThe exclusion has raised concerns among Somali officials and frequent travelers, who question why a close ally like Turkey would bypass Somalia in this initiative. Turkey has invested heavily in Somalia, including infrastructure projects, military training, and humanitarian aid, making the omission surprising to many observers.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this decision carries significant practical implications. Many Somalis rely on Turkey as a transit hub for travel, business, or education. The inability to use the e-Visa system adds inconvenience and potential delays, especially for those who need to travel urgently.\n\nThis development also highlights broader visa access challenges faced by Somali passport holders, who often encounter barriers when traveling internationally. While Turkey's expanded e-Visa program aims to facilitate tourism and business from select African countries, Somalia's exclusion suggests that security or bureaucratic concerns may still limit Ankara's willingness to extend the same privilege to its Somali partners.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/18/turkey-excludes-somalia-from-e-visa-expansion/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=turkey-excludes-somalia-from-e-visa-expansion",
